e Director, Ad Solutions (Ad Studio) Sharon Carter discusses what Black History Month means to her, Co-Chairing the NOIR ERG and the joy of unlocking your creativity. ","text":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTell us a little bit about yourself. How did you find your way to Condé Nast?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eCondé Nast was my target company to work for when I was in college. I would literally check the ‘Open Jobs’ section weekly to see if there were any roles that I could apply for. I looked at the job postings one day and there was an open role for an Ad Ops Specialist (I started my digital career in AdOps) so I applied and got the role. I’ve been at Condé Nast for over 7 years and I would not have it any other way. Working here has been a dream come true.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow do you describe your job to friends and family?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI originally told them I was the Olivia Pope of advertising to make things simple! But then I follow that up by saying I oversee the production and development of all our high impact and social display units. Like Deb Brett says, my team creates those gorgeous custom ads you see across the Condé Nast properties. If a client wants a performant and visual pleasing ad unit created, they come to my team and me.\u0026nbsp;\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou are co-chair of Condé Nast’s NOIR ERG (Employee Resource Group). What are your goals for the year?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI think doing internal programming for our African American employees is important, but we shouldn’t stop there. Building relationships with external organizations shows that Condé Nast cares about the African American community and that we are invested in making a global impact that brings about change. My other focus is making sure our African American employees feel heard and recognized by having town halls where they can voice their concerns and provide insight on the programming they want to see implemented here at Condé Nast.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBlack History Month is recognised in the U.S. during February. What does it mean for you?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eFor me, it’s a time of reflecting on how far we’ve come and the work that still needs to be done.\u0026nbsp; This month allows us to honor the leaders, past and present, who dedicated themselves to bringing about change even when the odds were against them. Some of my most fondest childhood memories are centered around BHM. Every year during grade school, I would do book reports on my favorite African American public figures, dress up as an activist for plays, and recite poems during my school’s annual program. And while those days are gone, as I got older celebrating my history became an everyday thing, not just during February.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat do you think is the most profound moment from African-American history in the U.S.?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eThe March on Washington in 1963 will always be near and dear to my heart. It was the catalyst for the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and it’s where Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his “I Have A Dream” speech. The power of Dr. King’s words and just seeing the images of the thousands of people that gathered to support the cause to support the rights of the Black community was and still is awe inspiring. I recited the “I Have A Dream” speech in grade school during a Black History Month program and I still have it memorized.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat’s the best piece of advice you’ve ever been given?\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eDon’t let doubt in. It’s easy to give up once you see things aren’t going your way but life is full of obstacles. Much like a track and field star, you have to find your way over the hurdles placed in front of you and keep going. The moment you let doubt in, is the moment you’ve given up.\u0026nbsp;\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is something you would like to do more of in 2024?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI would love to travel more in 2024. I was fortunate enough to go to four countries in six days last year. It was my own mini Renaissance Tour to elevate the adoption of the Ad Studio in Western Europe. I love learning about different cultures and looking at the architecture of the different buildings/landmarks.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIf you could do anything, besides what you’re doing now, what would you do?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eI love to draw, so being a cartoonist or illustrator would have been my alternative career path. I started drawing from a young age (I could draw before I could write, according to my mother) and still do to this day. I’ve illustrated hundreds of characters over the years. It’s a great stress-reliever. I think my artistic side has definitely helped me excel in the role I’m in now.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIf you had to spend 100 days on a desert island alone, what three things would you take with you and why?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;\"\u003eJust three? Since it’s a desert island I’m assuming there’s no electrical outlets so tablets and phones would be useless, haha. If I could bring other people, I’d bring my mom, dad and sister.\u0026nbsp; But if we’re talking about materialistic items, I would bring my drawing pad, pencil and a photo of my family. My mom, dad and sister are my three heartbeats and even now I wear one item of jewelry that represents each of them every day, so carrying a photo of them with me only makes sense. When it comes to the drawing pad and pencil, drawing is so therapeutic and a great way to pass the time. You don’t have to be Picasso to enjoy drawing and if I’m on a desert island I want to be able to do at least one thing I enjoy.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2024-02-12T00:00:00.000Z","isFeatured":false,"isHidden":false,"tag":null,"createdAt":"2024-02-12T16:22:37.563Z","updatedAt":"2024-02-12T16:22:52.478Z","publishedAt":"2024-02-12T16:22:44.807Z","locale":"en","Image":{"data":{"id":5220,"attributes":{"name":"Sharon Carter.j